title: For Sale:  Ottoman (Turkish) Flintlock Pistol
postcontent: Ottoman (Turkish) Flintlock Pistol. Circa 1750. Barrel length 14 ¾” and overall length 22”. Action works perfectly. This is a horseman’ style pistol and because of the size were carried in saddle holster. Ramrods were usually not provided on Middle East pistols and ramrod slot was either covered with decorated brass or silver or a false ramrod was part of the stock carving. The reason for this is that if the ramrod fell out of the pistol it was not reloadable. The owner kept the steel ramrod on his belt along with other items such as flints, powder, balls, etc. Most Middle East guns are fitted it this manor.Any questions? Please call Collectors Firearms at REDACTED ask for Daniel.Come by and visit us at 3301 Fondren Suite O, Houston,Tx 77063 For more photos click the link belowhttp://www.collectorsfirearms.com/ottoman-turkish-flintlock-pistol-ah4430/

title: For Sale:  Gamo 890 w/ BSA 3-12x50 scope
postcontent: Gamo Hunter 890 .177 cal. Piston air rifle. Single-shot 18.5” break-barrel, with muzzlebrake for extra cocking leverage (38 lbs. cocking effort), 7.5 lbs.. Muzzle velocity 1200 fps with PBA, 1000 fps with lead pellets. Adjustable 2-stage trigger, beech stock with checkered grip, raised cheekpiece on Monte Carlo buttstock with ventilated rubber buttpad. BSA Contender 3x-12x50mm w/ adjustable objective down to 12 yards ($120 new).  Review below found at: http://www.reviewcentre.com/Air-Rifles/Gamo-Hunter-890-177-cal--review_2076495, gave 5 stars for accuracy, handling, and value for the money.“The Gamo Hunter 890 Is A Winner!”“Written on: 07/06/2013 by WSellers3 (1 review written) This rifle has a bit more heft (and the same power plant) as the Gamo Shadow 1000. It is in the traditional wood and steel configuration of 2006-2007. It has been discontinued in the United States for about a year. My version is in .177. I can consistently hit the bullseye at 25 yards with this rifle and my scope of choice, the BSA 2X7X32 AO. The beech stock is beautiful, being comfortable and warm against the cheek when the rifle is shouldered. Overall weight comes in at just about 7 lbs. About the only thing I don't like is that its report is a tad loud, but luckily my neighbors in my home state of Louisiana don't seem to mind. When you see the single ragged hole in the middle of the bullseye after 5 shots, you'll fall in love with it and soon forget this minor shortcoming. The 890 is definitely capable of stellar accuracy.The rifle has plenty of power for small game hunting and plinking in the backyard. If you don't find one under the Gamo Hunter 890 name, you should know that the Gamo Silver Shadow Supreme is basically the same gun. The rifle comes with a scope stop; I would recommend a sturdy set of adjustable rings (such as Beeman 5030) for the 11mm dovetail be placed on this rifle, as recoil can be substantial. In recent years, the Gamo 890 has been marketed in the United States as a combo and sold with the BSA 3X12X50 AO scope. This is a great optic, but, in my opinion, this particular scope is a bit too large for the Gamo 890 and if you intend to use this scope, please do yourself a favor and buy a good steel 1-or 2-piece scope mount for the 11mm dovetail on this rifle. Overall, this is an excellent airgun for general purpose use, whether that use be hunting, pesting, or target practice. If you find one at a decent price, buy it. You won't be disappointed. “
